</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm221278704">
<problem id="fs-idm83914304">
<para id="fs-idm207552272">A 2.50-L volume of hydrogen measured at –196 °C is warmed to 100 °C. Calculate the volume of the gas at the higher temperature, assuming no change in pressure.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-idm213171488">
<para id="fs-idm179451664">12.1 L</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm179333888">
<problem id="fs-idm248411792">
<para id="fs-idm246603456">A balloon inflated with three breaths of air has a volume of 1.7 L. At the same temperature and pressure, what is the volume of the balloon if five more same-sized breaths are added to the balloon?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm24946256">
<problem id="fs-idm126307840">
<para id="fs-idp28199904">A weather balloon contains 8.80 moles of helium at a pressure of 0.992 atm and a temperature of 25 °C at ground level. What is the volume of the balloon under these conditions?</para>
<media id="fs-idm227684464" alt="This image shows a white balloon that appears to have an attached white card. The balloon is being held by a person in an outdoor setting." class="scaled-down">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_Chem_09_02_WeatherBall_img.jpg"/>
</media>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-idm78551216">
<para id="fs-idm244311136">217 L</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm207691136">
<problem id="fs-idm329170336">
